WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.560
 - Hello, and welcome to my lecture on cookies and sessions.

00:00:03.560 --> 00:00:07.720
 So taking a look at sort of how all this stuff works out,

00:00:07.720 --> 00:00:11.220
 we're again in our application.

00:00:11.220 --> 00:00:14.240
 So there's two distinct topics that we're going to cover,

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:17.680
 and it's really important to keep them clear.

00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:20.720
 So there's cookies, which are a browser concept.

00:00:20.720 --> 00:00:23.720
 And then there are sessions, which are a server concept.

00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:27.080
 When we write Python code in likeourviews.py,

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:29.160
 we talk to the session.

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:32.180
 Cookies are essential to sessions.

00:00:32.180 --> 00:00:35.280
 Cookies are used to look up which among the sessions

00:00:35.280 --> 00:00:36.920
 that we're going to use.

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:38.640
 So what we're gonna do is I'm gonna first talk about

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:39.840
 really just the cookies.

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:43.520
 How cookies talk, how the servers talk to the cookies,

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:45.560
 and then separately we'll talk about sessions.

00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:48.020
 So keep the two concepts the same.

00:00:48.020 --> 00:00:50.320
 A lot of people tend to confuse the concept

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:51.400
 of sessions and cookies,

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:53.760
 'cause one of the most common use of cookies

00:00:53.760 --> 00:00:57.320
 is to establish and maintain sessions.

00:00:57.320 --> 00:01:02.020
 So the first thing about the web in general

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:04.800
 is that you have a web server,

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:06.160
 and when you're just developing,

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:07.620
 you think there's only one person,

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:09.980
 which is you, talking to the web server.

00:01:09.980 --> 00:01:12.360
 But in reality, when a web server's in production,

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:13.260
 connected to the internet,

00:01:13.260 --> 00:01:14.880
 there could be 1,000 connections

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:16.880
 to 1,000 different browsers.

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:19.880
 And it's essential that the server can figure out

00:01:19.880 --> 00:01:23.760
 at any moment which browser it is talking to.

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:26.160
 We don't maintain a permanent connection to these browsers.

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:28.000
 That's one of the reasons that the internet scales

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
 as high as it does, right?

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.440
 But that's, so we still have to have some way

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:37.240
 of distinguishing when a request comes in from this server

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:39.480
 versus when it comes in from that server.

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:41.400
 And so what we wanna do is we want a way

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:44.400
 to basically put a little mark on each browser

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:46.000
 and say, oh, that's this browser.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.680
 And so when you log in from this browser,

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:50.640
 I can know that it's you.

00:01:50.640 --> 00:01:53.440
 So marking the browser is different from saying,

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:56.180
 I have browser 41, 42, 43, 44.

00:01:56.180 --> 00:02:00.000
 And each browser ends up with a mark.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.200
 In the early days, the web was pretty much

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:04.120
 a read-only medium.

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:05.680
 We didn't do a lot of logging in.

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:07.880
 We didn't do a lot of uploading.

00:02:07.880 --> 00:02:09.200
 There were password mechanisms,

00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:11.320
 but they were very, very clunky.

00:02:11.320 --> 00:02:14.080
 And so all the browsers were pretty much reading

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:16.440
 the same information, and as long as you're not logging in

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:20.520
 and modifying stuff, it just doesn't matter.

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:23.760
 So quickly, in the early days of the web,

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:25.480
 the idea of a cookie was created,

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:28.640
 and that was a way for the server

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:32.120
 to store a little bit of data on each of the browsers.

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:33.760
 And they're just little pieces of data

00:02:33.760 --> 00:02:36.800
 written by the servers, read by the servers,

00:02:36.800 --> 00:02:40.080
 sent by the browsers, and read by the servers.

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:42.000
 Now, it has nothing to do with logging in.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:44.380
 It has to do with writing a little mark on every browser

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:48.160
 and then getting that browser mark back every time we ask it.

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:53.160
 So often when a server gets a first request from a web page

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:55.600
 that doesn't have its little mark on it,

00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:57.880
 it makes up a number and sends that cookie back.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:01.440
 So it sets the cookie, there may be many interactions

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:04.800
 between the time you're starting to talk to a server

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:06.080
 and when you log in.

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:08.640
 But often the cookie is set immediately.

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:12.560
 But the key is, is that once I set that cookie,

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:15.640
 it's like storage for my server on your browser,

00:03:15.640 --> 00:03:19.200
 and each of the servers, and that can be sort of

00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:22.020
 temporary or permanent storage.

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:24.280
 So they're marked in the browser

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:25.960
 by the web address as they came from.

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:27.120
 It's a security thing.

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:31.520
 You're not allowed to read cookies from a page.

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:33.360
 If your page comes from a particular server,

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:35.240
 it can only read the cookies associated with that server

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:39.820
 and vice versa, so they're like a little stovepiped.

00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:41.440
 Cookies have an expiration date.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:43.440
 There is two kinds of expiration dates.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:46.160
 There's sort of a by a certain time or a number of seconds,

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:50.080
 or there is stay logged in or keep this cookie

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:54.960
 until the browser is shut down.

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:56.800
 We call those session cookies,

00:03:56.800 --> 00:03:58.760
 which is kind of weird 'cause we often use them.

00:03:58.760 --> 00:04:01.280
 We often use session cookies for sessions,

00:04:01.280 --> 00:04:03.560
 but we still gotta keep them cookies.

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:05.520
 So here's a bit of sample code.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:09.040
 So one of the things you can do is you can go

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:11.000
 into your browser console and you find something

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.120
 like storage, and you can see for the website

00:04:14.120 --> 00:04:17.880
 of the current page, the current website that you're on,

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:20.120
 that website's cookies are stored here.

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:21.880
 And so I'm looking at the cookies here,

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:25.480
 and I see there's only one cookie, the CFDUID.

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:30.480
 That's the server is using a proxy to help speed itself up.

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:34.720
 And so that cookie's not really part of our application.

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:36.840
 And so what happens is there is no cookie.

00:04:36.840 --> 00:04:38.080
 It's not set.

00:04:38.080 --> 00:04:40.840
 And so we go in and click on this.

00:04:40.840 --> 00:04:42.760
 If you give a browser a cookie.

00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:45.760
 And it's going to route to this particular view.

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:49.920
 And so in this, we're gonna do a print of request.cookies.

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:52.960
 So what happens is I mention that every time

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:56.120
 a web request comes in, all the cookies get sent in

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:58.860
 with that web request that are associated with that server.

00:04:58.860 --> 00:04:59.700
 So we're gonna print them out.

00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:03.000
 And they come in just like request.get, request.post,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.480
 and request.cookies is Django's way

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:07.640
 of handing us all that information.

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:11.100
 And so in this case, I'm not actually going

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:13.880
 to send the response back in the return value.

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:15.600
 I'm actually gonna create the response.

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:18.480
 That's resphd response with a string.

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:20.480
 And then I'm gonna set some cookies.

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:22.760
 So cookies are part of the response.

00:05:22.760 --> 00:05:25.840
 They're actually part of the headers of the response.

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:27.440
 And I'm gonna just set one cookie.

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:28.280
 They're my names.

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:30.420
 I set 'em, this application.

00:05:30.420 --> 00:05:31.960
 Cookie name zap to 42.

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:35.840
 And then a cookie named SakaiCar with a value of 42.

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:37.440
 And I give it 1,000 seconds.

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:40.800
 So that's, one is a session cookie,

00:05:40.800 --> 00:05:43.440
 and the other is a cookie with a fixed expiration date.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:45.040
 Now this 1,000 seconds,

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:46.960
 you can go much longer than 1,000 seconds

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:48.640
 if you start looking at the cookies

00:05:48.640 --> 00:05:51.360
 that you're talking to on the various things.

00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:53.680
 These are year-long, multi-year cookies,

00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:54.920
 et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:05:54.920 --> 00:05:56.920
 And so if you were to see the printout

00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:59.160
 that is coming from that request.cookies,

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:00.400
 you would see that it's basically

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:02.640
 a dictionary of key value pairs.

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:05.300
 Now that's after the second response.

00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:09.120
 So if we go and we click on the cookie

00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:11.220
 and we start with no cookies whatsoever,

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:14.400
 if we start with no cookies whatsoever,

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:17.700
 we're gonna send this code out,

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:20.200
 and it's gonna send two cookies back.

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:22.440
 And so what you can see here is you can see,

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:26.240
 if you look closely on the response headers,

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:28.340
 two set cookie responses.

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:31.800
 So the response headers are like the content type,

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:32.860
 et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:06:32.860 --> 00:06:34.440
 They're not the actual page.

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:36.560
 The actual page is C is for cookie and it's good enough

00:06:36.560 --> 00:06:40.480
 for me, but basically when this response came back,

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.260
 the server said, hey, set this key value pair

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:46.560
 and this key value pair and have this second one expire,

00:06:46.560 --> 00:06:50.040
 which is exactly what I did inside that code.

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:52.080
 And so now if we take a quick look

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:53.600
 and we take a look in our storage,

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:56.760
 what we're gonna see is that we now have two values.

00:06:56.760 --> 00:07:01.040
 Sakai car is 42, Zap is also 42,

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:03.280
 Sakai car is going to expire a certain amount

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:06.440
 of time in the future and Zap is a session cookie

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:08.100
 'cause we gave it with no expiration,

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:10.320
 which means once I wanna close all the tabs

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:12.020
 in my browser and close the browser,

00:07:12.020 --> 00:07:14.100
 then the browser will throw this away.

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:18.240
 The Sakai car will be persisted to disk or some other place

00:07:18.240 --> 00:07:22.160
 so that if I close all my browsers and open browsers up

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:25.480
 and go back to this website, samplesdj4e.com,

00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:26.800
 it'll start sending that cookie.

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:30.000
 So that's a permanent cookie with an expiration date on it.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:31.400
 Now that's pretty short expiration,

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:35.160
 1,000 seconds is like, what, 20 minutes, I think,

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:36.680
 and so that's gonna go away.

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:39.200
 But a lot of these cookies last much longer.

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:44.120
 So that's after the set cookie comes back from the server,

00:07:44.120 --> 00:07:47.800
 then we can take a look and we can see

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:50.680
 as we make another request, we're going to see

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:54.800
 that the browser is going to look up the cookies

00:07:54.800 --> 00:07:57.400
 and we have this one here that's part

00:07:57.400 --> 00:08:01.200
 of the hosting environment, but Zap equals 42 Sakai car.

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:03.340
 So now in goes a get request

00:08:03.340 --> 00:08:05.640
 and as part of the request headers,

00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:07.980
 it's telling us all the cookie values

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:10.880
 for samples.dj4e.com.

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:13.920
 And then when I look at my code and I say request.cookies,

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.720
 request.cookies contains the parsed versions

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:19.160
 of Zap 42 and Sakai car 42.

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:21.860
 So I'm gonna end up with a dictionary with two values in it

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:24.000
 and Zap and Sakai car.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.360
 And so the way to think about this is

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:29.760
 when the browser first come in,

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:34.640
 first comes in to the server, it looks for the cookie.

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:36.680
 It might say, do I have this cookie already set?

00:08:36.680 --> 00:08:39.840
 Now my application that I wrote is real simple.

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:42.340
 And then you are gonna send the cookie back

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:45.880
 and then the browser stores the cookie inside the browser

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:48.000
 and then from that point forward,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.160
 every time it makes a request, that comes in

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:56.040
 and we can see this in the variable request.cookies inside it.

00:08:56.040 --> 00:08:58.120
 So we really only have to set it once,

00:08:58.120 --> 00:09:00.040
 although the code I wrote sets it every time,

00:09:00.040 --> 00:09:01.880
 but it doesn't matter.

00:09:01.880 --> 00:09:04.680
 Until it expires or until the browser closes,

00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:09.160
 the job of the browser is to send that cookie back, okay?

00:09:09.160 --> 00:09:11.800
 So remember what I said, I said we're gonna mark this

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:13.680
 each browser with a different number

00:09:13.680 --> 00:09:15.280
 so we can know which browser is which.

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:16.440
 That's exactly what it is.

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:18.240
 Now it doesn't always set it to 42.

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:21.180
 Usually it chooses a large random number,

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:23.160
 but we'll get to that in a second.

00:09:23.160 --> 00:09:26.060
 So up next, we're gonna like make some sense of this

00:09:26.060 --> 00:09:27.960
 by adding the backend part of this,

00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:31.520
 which is the sessions, which stores all the data

00:09:31.520 --> 00:09:32.860
 from request to request.

00:09:32.860 --> 00:09:35.440
 (upbeat music)

